# TypeScript Conventions

Lexsys targets **strict, modern TypeScript 6.x**. All packages share the same baseline via `tsconfig.base.json` (`strict`, `isolatedModules`, `moduleResolution: Bundler`).

Related: [tech-stack.mdc](./tech-stack.mdc), [docs/contributors/STYLE.md](../../docs/contributors/STYLE.md).

---

## Import style

Use `import type` for type-only symbols. Two valid forms — pick the one that reads cleaner:

```typescript
// Separate line (prefer when all imports are types)
import type { ButtonProps } from "./Button.types.js"

// Inline type (prefer when mixing value + type from same module)
import { clsx, type ClassValue } from "clsx"
import { createResult, type InstallResourceResult } from "./results.js"
```

```typescript
// Bad — imports type as value (wastes bundle space, breaks isolatedModules)
import { ButtonProps } from "./Button.types.js"

// Bad — two separate import lines from same module
import { createResult } from "./results.js"
import type { InstallResourceResult } from "./results.js"
```

---

## No `any`

Never use `any` — explicit or implicit. At runtime boundaries (JSON parse, config read, CLI args), narrow from `unknown`:

```typescript
// Good — narrow from unknown
const parsed = JSON.parse(content) as Record<string, unknown>
const name = typeof parsed.name === "string" ? parsed.name : undefined

// Good — type guard narrows unknown
const isError = (value: unknown): value is Error => value instanceof Error

// Bad
const parsed = JSON.parse(content) as any
```

`// @ts-ignore` requires a one-line comment explaining why. Prefer `// @ts-expect-error` when the issue is a known upstream bug.

---

## Error handling

Always type the catch variable as `unknown`. Narrow before use:

```typescript
// Good
} catch (error: unknown) {
  const message = error instanceof Error ? error.message : String(error)
}

// Good — re-throw when no recovery possible
} catch (error: unknown) {
  if (isNotFoundError(error)) return false
  throw error
}

// Bad — untyped catch (implicit unknown, but explicit is clearer and required by convention)
} catch (error) {
  console.log(error.message) // unsafe
}
```

Use `CliError` for user-facing CLI failures. Let `handleCliError` in `utils/cli-error.ts` be the single exit point:

```typescript
throw new CliError("Config not found.", "Run `lexsys init` first.")
```

