## `interface` vs `type`

| Use `interface` for | Use `type` for |
| --- | --- |
| Object prop shapes that may be extended (`extends`) | Unions (`"a" \| "b"`) |
| Component props (`ButtonProps extends Omit<...>`) | Mapped / indexed access types |
| Internal context shapes | Generic aliases (`type Fn<T> = (x: T) => void`) |

```typescript
// Good
export interface ButtonProps extends Omit<BaseButton.Root.Props, "className"> {
  variant?: ButtonVariant
}

export type ButtonVariant = "primary" | "secondary" | "ghost" | "danger"

// Bad — union as interface
export interface ButtonVariant {
  value: "primary" | "secondary"
}
```

---

## No enums

Use string literal unions and `as const` tuples — not TypeScript `enum`.

```typescript
// Good
export type RegistryItemType = "component" | "block" | "utility" | "style"

const LAYERS = ["primitive", "block", "template"] as const
type Layer = (typeof LAYERS)[number]

// Bad
enum RegistryItemType { Component = "component", Block = "block" }
```

---

## `export const` style

Always use `export const` arrow functions. Never `export function`.

```typescript
// Good
export const resolveItemInstallTarget = (
  config: LexsysConfig,
  item: RegistryItem,
): string => { ... }

// Bad
export function resolveItemInstallTarget(config, item) { ... }
```

UI components: define as `const`, attach `displayName`, export in a named block at the bottom:

```typescript
const Button = ({ ref, variant, ...props }: ButtonProps) => { ... }
Button.displayName = "Button"
export { Button }
```

---

## Type assertions

Prefer type guards over assertions. When assertions are necessary, cast through `unknown` — not directly across unrelated types:

```typescript
// Good — guard narrows
const isStyle = (value: unknown): value is RegistryStyle => { ... }

// Acceptable — JSON parse boundary
const doc = JSON.parse(content) as unknown as DtcgTokenDocument

// Bad — direct cast across unrelated types
const items = rawItems as ResolvedItems
```

Never use the non-null `!` operator. Prefer explicit null checks or type guards.

---

## `readonly` and immutability

Use `readonly` on schema/config arrays in tokens and registry where mutation would be a bug:

```typescript
// Good
readonly path: readonly string[]
TThemeModes extends readonly ThemeModeId[]
```

UI prop interfaces do not require `readonly` — React immutability conventions apply instead.

---

## ESM and module hygiene

- All imports use `import` / `export` — no `require()`
- Relative imports inside `packages/*/src/` must include `.js` extension (resolves to `.ts` at build time via `moduleResolution: NodeNext` for cli/registry)
- Never deep-import another package's `src/` or internal `dist/` paths — only `package.json` exports

```typescript
// Good
import { loadConfig } from "../config/config.js"
import type { LexsysConfig } from "@dalexto/lexsys-registry"

// Bad
import { loadConfig } from "../config/config"       // missing .js
import { something } from "@dalexto/lexsys-cli/src/utils/flags" // deep import
```
